<BaseLayout title="About">
  <h1>About this project</h1>

  <section class="dedication">
    <h2>Dedication</h2>
    <p>
      This work is offered in humble remembrance of
      <strong>Srimad Uttamur Veeraraghavachariar Swamy</strong> (1897–1983), the revered
      Sri Vaishnava acharya and scholar, in whose parampara it is carried forward. Among
      his many works, he composed a Tamil commentary (<em>urai</em>) on the
      <strong>Sankshepa Ramayana</strong> — the "Ramayana in brief," the opening sarga of
      Valmiki's Bala Kanda in which Narada narrates the whole epic in a hundred verses.
    </p>
    <p>
      It is also offered at the feet of the acharyas of this lineage —
      <strong>Shri Ramanujacharya</strong>, <strong>Srimad Vedanta Desikan</strong>, and
      the acharyas of the Parakala Matha.
    </p>
    <p>
      Swamy also composed an <a href="/eka-sloki"><strong>Eka-Śloki Rāmāyaṇam</strong></a> —
      the entire epic distilled into a single verse.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2>What this is</h2>
  <p>A study repository connecting Kamban's Ramayanam
     (<span lang="ta">கம்பராமாயணம்</span>) to the wider Sri Vaishnava and
     Sanskrit tradition, read through the Vishishtadvaita (viśiṣṭādvaita) lens.</p>
  <h2>Sources & copyright</h2>
  <p>The Kamba Ramayanam <strong>Tamil text and padalam structure</strong> follow the
     public-domain edition (மூலமும் உரையும்) of the Kamban Trust / tamilvu.org. The
     <strong>English translation</strong> follows the rendering of the late
     <strong>P.S. Sundaram</strong>, cited with gratitude. We also cite and deep-link to
     authoritative sources for the compared texts (e.g. valmikiramayan.net,
     holy-bhagavad-gita.org), quoting only short excerpts. Full texts remain with their
     sources.</p>
  <h2>How content is verified</h2>
  <p>Content is AI-assisted and then human-verified. Every entry carries a status —
     <strong>draft</strong>, <strong>verified</strong>, or <strong>published</strong>.
     Anything not yet published is visibly marked, so nothing unverified is presented
     as authoritative.</p>
  <h2>Imagery</h2>
  <p>All images are original Tanjore-style paintings, reviewed for iconographic accuracy.</p>
</BaseLayout>
